13/08/2009
ANKARA, Turkey -- A senior member of the ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) suggested on Wednesday (August 12th) that Kurdish rebel leaders be exiled and remaining militants be pardoned as part of the government's initiative to end the 25-year Kurdish insurgency. In remarks published by the Milliyet newspaper, Dengir Mir Mehmet Firat, a Kurd who was formerly deputy leader of the AKP, noted that the list of senior members of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) drafted by Ankara includes around 200 names of people based in northern Iraq. (AFP, Turkish Weekly - 13/08/09; Milliyet - 12/08/09)
